# Minitron - Cursor Rules

## Project
Electron + React + TypeScript desktop app wrapping OpenClaw through a local Express control layer.

## Always
- Use strict TypeScript
- Use Zod for API input validation
- Catch and handle async failures
- Route all renderer requests through `/core` APIs
- Encrypt API keys with AES-256-GCM before persistence
- Log user actions to audit history
- Put every UI string in i18n files first

## Never
- Modify `/vendor/openclaw/`
- Connect renderer directly to OpenClaw WebSocket
- Rebuild OpenClaw channels/routing/session runtime
- Rebuild Cognee in Node.js
- Hardcode UI strings
- Use `any` unless absolutely unavoidable

## i18n
- Mandatory from day 1 via react-i18next
- Key format: `namespace.category.item`
- Start in English and expand language files incrementally
- Handle RTL languages by setting `document.documentElement.dir`

## Security
- Sanitize and validate all inputs
- Validate paths against workspace root
- Never log secrets
- Support sandboxed execution for untrusted tasks
